article.description:
Phoenix Suns continued their winning ways,
even without Shawn Marion.
article.headline: Marion goes down, but Marbury, Jacobsen pick up slack

images.name: Voskuhl Jake 021227 inline
images.caption: Clippers center Wang ZhiZhi, left, has a rebound grabbed away by Suns center Jake Voskuhl.

article.linkText: Suns keep getting hotter, even without Marion
article.story:
PHOENIX (AP) -- The Phoenix Suns continued their winning ways, even without Shawn Marion. The Suns lost Marion, their leading scorer and rebounder, to a sprained ankle early in the second half, and still won their fourth in a row -- 108-95 over the Los Angeles Clippers on Friday night. Stephon Marbury scored 26 points and rookie Casey Jacobsen added a career-high 19. Jacobsen went 5-for-7 from 3-point range for the surprising Suns, who have won eight of nine, six in a row at home. ''I've got to give the credit to Steph,'' Jacobsen said. ''The last five 3s I took, there wasn't a person within 10 feet of me.'' Phoenix is tied with San Antonio for the third-best record in the Western Conference (18-11). ''We're playing hard, smart and together,'' Marbury said. ''That's all you can ask for.'' Marion, averaging 20.6 points and 10 rebounds for Phoenix, was helped from the court after spraining his left ankle with 10:59 left in the third quarter. X-rays were negative, but he did not return. Teams often turn to a zone defense against Phoenix because of the team's suspect shooting, but Jacobsen is helping change that. ''We took a team out of a zone,'' Phoenix coach Frank Johnson said. ''Can you believe that?'' Despite foul trouble, Elton Brand scored 29 points in 31 minutes for Los Angeles after missing two games with a strained right calf. ''He played well,'' Los Angeles coach Alvin Gentry said. ''But I knew he would play well. The only thing that kind of surprised me is he only had eight rebounds.'' Rookie Amare Stoudemire added 16 points and eight rebounds, and Penny Hardaway had 13 points and 10 assists for Phoenix. Marion scored 14 in 15 minutes. Quentin Richardson added 16 points for Los Angeles. Corey Maggette, back after missing 14 games following arthroscopic surgery on his right knee, scored 11 points in 18 minutes, all in the second half. The Suns never trailed and led by as many as 22 early in the fourth quarter, but the Clippers rallied. Brand scored six in a 15-2 run that cut the lead to 90-81 with 6:35 remaining. Marbury's 18-footer boosted the lead to 92-81, then Randy Brown, just off the injured list, made a 13-footer from the baseline, then a layup and Phoenix led 96-82 with 4:53 to go. The Clippers never got closer than 10 again. With Marion out, Marbury picked up the slack. He drew Brand's fifth foul on a driving layup for a three-point play that made it 70-60 with 4:52 left in the third quarter, then scored again inside to put the Suns up 72-60 with 4:23 to go in the third. The two plays exemplified how difficult a time the Clippers have had with Phoenix's high screen-and-roll play. ''We couldn't get Steph under control,'' Gentry said. Marbury's five points ignited an 13-2 outburst that gave Phoenix an 80-62 lead on Bo Outlaw's layup with 1:47 left in the third. Jacobsen's two free throws gave Phoenix an 82-62 edge and the Suns led 84-66 entering the fourth. Hardaway's 22-footer gave Phoenix its biggest lead at 88-66 with 11:07 to play. ''We felt we had to step up because one of our best players was down,'' Stoudemire said. ''We didn't want the Clippers to take advantage of it, so we came out with a lot more intensity after he went out.'' Game notes
The Clippers lost to the Suns for the second time in seven days. ... To make room for Brown, Phoenix placed forward Alton Ford on the injured list with a right ankle sprain. ... Phoenix's lone defeat in its last nine games was at Sacramento. ... Brand was 7-for-9 from the field and scored 14 of the Clippers' 22 points in the first quarter. ... Los Angeles is 1-7 against Pacific Division foes.
